description:
You are the Red Joker. Find and kill your evil twin, the Black Joker.

Players layout number cards to represent Rooms, Doors, and Levels, battle Jacks, Kings, and Queens with hit points,search for the Black Joker through up to ten levels in an ever changing maze dealt with a simple deck of standard playing cards. A Quick reference book lays out the mechanisms for movement, combat, Hand-management, and for finding and fighting the Black Joker.

&ldquo;All my life I&rsquo;ve known my brother was the evil twin. I&rsquo;ve always felt that one of us shouldn&rsquo;t have been born. Today, one of us dies in Blackie&rsquo;s Maze.&rdquo;

A quiz game aimed at children. The questions are all related to the theme, in this case, dinosaurs. You are given three possible answers and so if you don't know, you can have fun guessing.

The player who answers the most questions correctly, wins. As a little extra, each player can check their score against a table and will be rated as:
A Super-Meister-Quizdetectiv, or;
A Meister Quizdetectiv, or;
A Quizdetectiv, or:
A Hilfs-Quizdetectiv

Objective: be the first reaching the target

- acting/moving by turn -
roll the die and use points to move your meeple and/or dig
 - one point per movement/digging;
digging means => put slides on the board or move/turn them;
players may start with a certain no. of obstacles (danger cards - max. 6) which are going to spoil movement.

Objective: be the first to pass finish line (100)
 - acting by turn -
throw both dice (1d6 & 5-coloured+joker one):
colour defines the question card to draw 
number determines the question to answer and - if correct - spaces to move forward;
starting from a pink space (luck) you may double allowed distance;
starting from a risk space you must move back if answer is wrong;
the very last (coloured) spaces must be taken step by step (no jump), card to be drawn determined by colour (no die).

The film is over budget. The script is late. There are only three days left of filming. Your team of grips and electricians must scramble to film as many scenes as possible before production wraps! Don&rsquo;t worry, though: &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll fix it in post.&rdquo;

In Grips & Gaffers, you are responsible for a production unit filming footage for a movie. Your film set is a "puzzle" in which you attempt to slide the cameras, lights, and director around the board to match the needs of one of the scenes to be filmed. At the same time, every other player is racing to film the same scenes. If they get there first, you may be out of luck; you can only film a scene if the actors aren't busy on another set. Sometimes it might be necessary to film when the set is "close enough," rather than taking the time to earn a bonus for a perfect setup.

Time is of the essence! Every camera movement advances your Gaffer pawn on the time track, while lighting changes advance your Key Grip pawn. The player whose pawn is at the rear of the track moves next, so being efficient&mdash;and balancing the amount of work your grips and your electricians do&mdash;is key to your filmmaking success!

Objective: flip most of your pearls into opponents area
 - acting by turn/2 players or 2 teams -
create 2 equal areas;
each player flips a pearl (of 10) into opponent's area (crossing own area);
move a pearl only once, but bumping (like curling) to optimize position is allowed; pearls outside the 2 areas are out of game.

remarks: Tabaluga is a cartoon character created by Peter Maffay, Rolf Zuckowski, Gregor Rottschalk, Helme Heine

Objective: be the first distributing your invitations and solving your quests
 - acting by turn -
draw your quest cards first;
throw the die - move fore- or backwards (if there isn't any obstacle like a garbage bin);
ending on a marked space perform required action in order to get rid of one of your quests/invitation card

objective: gather as few as possible of those 'snow-tiles';
 - acting/moving by turn - 
active player throws the die & moves forward;
if there is no land inside of the race track ==> uncover a slide: Green? ==> place it upon a snowy region; White? ==> keep it (penalty point) 
if there is another player and/or green land you end on - nothing happens;
if there is another player with less penalty points: turn over a white (penalty) slide;
game ends if there is 'green' all over inside - player with less penalty slides wins

In this special edition of Spiel des Wissens, based on the BBC TV series and the film of the same name, players travel round our planet. To be able to travel the must be able to answer questions. In this edition questions come from a general category called Nature and from 6 special so called worlds &ndash; mountain world, jungle world, ice world, cave world, deep sea world and desert world.  &ndash;

On each question cards questions are separated into an easy and a hard section, two in each section. At the start of the game players decide together who gets which difficulty level throughout the game. Before each question the player decides if wants to answer question 1 or question 2 on the card.

You roll the die, move and answer a question.

Objective: be the first moving your 3 meeples into target zone
 - moving by turns -
throw the die and move according rolled number;
you need a '6' to step out and a '6' for an additional move;
target zone can be reached passing the turntable only;
if a meeple blocks/sits on a 'D' space turntable may be moved;
you may jump over other meeples, but your own one blocks you.
remarks:
published before/during WWII

Objective: get as many cards as possible
 - acting simultaneously -
place 8 cards uncovered upon the table;
distribute remainig cards among players, forming a staple;
simultaneously all players uncover their top one;
if there is a matching one in the middle - grasp at it as fast as possible.
Successfully catching a card players have to form a 'loot' staple, on top last obtained card, uncovered! If a player uncovers a matching card during next turns the whole staple can be caught. Game ends after all 8 cards are picked up.

Objective: gain most balls (chips) scoring goals
 - acting by turns -
3 x 3 slides light, middle and dark green are positioned, forming a square with 3 rows respectively. In each row  there are hidden the same three faces shown on a die: Justus, Peter, Bob;
active player throws the die; matching slide of the 'light green' row must be turned/shown and flip again to step ahead;
if player reaches the 'dark green' row there are 3 attempts to score a goal by using the approach of 'Tiddledy Winks'; successful? A ball (chip) is won out of supply - failed: A ball is lost out of supply.
Remarks: No. of balls in supply determine length of a game

Objective: gain as many cards (max. 5) as possible forming/collecting a set of same images
 - acting by turns -
form two piles - draw and drop (trash); the very last card of the trash (7 in the beginning) remains visible, all other cards are hidden; each player is dealt 5 (maximum amount) cards.
active player throws the die: 
card? Draw a card;
question mark? Look through the trash and draw a card;
thunderbolt? If you don't own the 'yellow card' - draw a card from another player and flip a round marker (totally 7);
if you possess the yellow card: draw a card as usual;
the player who lost a card gets the 'yellow card'; 
at the end of a draw all players must reduce/fill their no. of cards up to 5 .
Game ends if all round marker are flipped or if one player owns a set of 5 identical cards.

Objective: be the first collecting 6 cookies
 - acting by turns -
the board is prepared - 6x6 grid - covered by small slides;
active player rolls 2 dice (1D6 + coloured);
the slide with these 'coordinates' tells ypu what to do:
take cookies, get one mouse (or even 2 mice) => leads to cookoies consumption, witch...

Combat Commander: Battle Pack #5 &ndash; Fall of the West is the fifth themed collection of scenarios for use with the Combat Commander series of games. The theme of this Battle Pack shifts to actions in France, Belgium and Norway from late April to June 1940, looking at critical moments in this brief span where the forces of both sides tested each other sorely. To reflect this, the scenario special rules are designed to make the Allied Minor hand exhibit flexibility (which was demonstrated whenever higher echelon interference was reduced). CC&ndash;Fall of the West features twelve new scenarios printed on cardstock as well as ten new maps.

Special experimental AFV Rules are featured in four of the scenarios where tanks are facing infantry in settings that reveal how the doctrines, armaments and countermeasures were still early in development. While unfettered races by companies of tanks across the countryside remain a landmark image of the blitzkrieg, we found many instances of a more tentative level of engagement, suitable for our attempt at capturing an unusual element in the CC scope &ndash; TANKS!
 The new maps depict specific locations in France, Belgium and Norway, which have been located and specifically verified (from the sky, maps and in texts). The player will discover the actual names of roads and other terrain features as a reminder of the reality of the events.
 The scenarios included in CC&ndash;Fall of the West are:


74 &ndash; &ldquo;Sturmgruppe Granit&rdquo; starts with the daring glider landings on top of Fort Eben Emael and serves as the opening to the Fall of the West, 10 May 1940;
75 &ndash; &ldquo;Sturmgruppe Beton&rdquo; set near Maastricht, Belgium with another element of the glider landings facing fierce counterattack by Belgian forces , 10 May 1940;
76 &ndash; &ldquo;A Most Gallant Dirty Little Imp&rdquo;, set at the Dyle River, Belgium, featuring heroic leadership by the first winner of the Victoria Cross in WW2, 15 May 1940;
77 &ndash; &ldquo;The Crucible of Fire&rdquo; set at Petegem, Belgium, during the early tactical withdrawal of the BEF &ndash; features the Bren Carrier, 21 May 1940;
78 &ndash; &ldquo;By These Deeds They Shall Be Known&rdquo; set in Cassel, France during the desperate rearguard work by the BEF to protect the Port of Dunkirk, 27 May 1940;
79 &ndash; &ldquo;Battering Ram at Kvam&rdquo; set in the Gudbrandsdal Valley in Norway with valiant British defenders facing heavy German assault by tanks and bombers, 26 April 1940;
80 &ndash; &ldquo;Bitter Isthmus&rdquo; set at the French frontier town of Montherm&eacute;, showing that locally the French were equal to the test set before them, 14 May 1940;
81 &ndash; &ldquo;The Bottleneck&rdquo; set near Sedan, France in a fluid seesaw moment during the swift German advance &ndash; features the FCM 36, 14 May 1940;
82 &ndash; &ldquo;Hidden Guns Lash Out&rdquo; set at the outskirts of Gembloux, France, where defiant, capable defenders held off a major German assault &ndash; features the PzKfw III, 14 June 1940;
83 &ndash; &ldquo;Thrust in the Dust&rdquo; covers the zenith of the heroic French anti-tank defense of Gembloux, facing waves of German armor, 15 June 1940;
84 &ndash; &ldquo;Seize the Canal&rdquo; set at Ch&acirc;teau-Porcien, France on the River Aisne, with a heavy urban assault by German forces seeking to breech the river line, 9 June 1940;
85 &ndash; &ldquo;The Striking Hammer&rdquo; features a  major armored counterattack against the German-held positions at Perthes, France &ndash; features the Char B1bis, 10 June 1940;


NOTE: CC&ndash;Fall of the West is not a complete game and requires ownership of Combat Commander: Europe and Combat Commander: Mediterranean to play.
 Designed by John A. Foley and Bryan Collars
Developed by Bryan Collars

Objective: find out which 4 animals/persons (out of 12) are potential subject of a crime
 - acting simultaneously -
offender = game master (changes per round) takes 4 (out of 12) hidden cards;
active player rolls the die & turns as many of (correspondent) detective cards; game master responds with correct answer;
e.g.: player rolls a '5' & draws 5 detective cards - if 2 of them are matching result becomes '2' (similar to Mastermind).
After 8 turns players must judge; each matching 'hit' let players move up their scoring position, a mismatch moves the black offender's one; new round...
at the end: top position wins; 
if black offender's position is top - all lost.

STRYKER-20 puts you in command of a US Army Stryker mechanized unit against an OPFOR (Opposition Forces) formation. This is a two player game: US Player and OPFOR Player. The US Player controls the Stryker Combat Team. There are two levels of scenario: Company Commander to provide an introduction to the missions; and battalion, to provide a full simulation.

The Opposition Forces (OPFOR) player controls enemy units and also manages various randomized incidents within the area of operations. The game also can be played by teams of players, each commanding different element of a force.&nbsp;

As much as possible, STRYKER uses standard US military terminology to create a simulation experience that can be used by service members with a minimum of special knowledge of gaming, and can also be used to train civilian personnel in military procedure.

General Course of Play

Each player selects a Mission card from the deck. You organize your Stryker Combat Team, which, depending on the scenario, may be one company, two companies, or a full battalion. You then deploy your Team on the game map.&nbsp;

The basic unit in the game is a platoon (some units represent smaller teams/squads). There are also markers representing various kinds of Fire and Surveillance Support, as well as civilians and items which would appear in a combat zone.&nbsp;

The game is played in scenarios, called Missions. To win a scenario, you must accomplish your mission objective.&nbsp;
